Software Architectures
======================
The MVC structure stands for Model–View–Controller, a common architectural pattern used in software development
(especially in web apps) to organize code cleanly and separate concerns.

Here’s a simple breakdown:

🔹 1. Model

The Model handles the data and business logic.

Manages data (database, APIs, etc.)
Contains rules, calculations, and core functionality
Not concerned with how data is displayed

👉 Example:
If you're building a blog app, the model handles posts, users, comments, and database operations.

🔹 2. View

The View is the user interface (UI).

Displays data to the user
Receives input (forms, clicks)
Doesn’t contain business logic

👉 Example:
HTML pages, UI templates, or frontend components showing blog posts.

🔹 3. Controller

The Controller acts as the middleman between Model and View.

Receives user input
Processes requests
Calls the Model to get/update data
Sends data to the View

👉 Example:
When a user clicks “Submit Post,” the controller:

Receives the request
Tells the model to save the post
Returns a success page (view)
🔄 How They Work Together
User interacts with the View
The Controller handles the request
The Model processes data
The View displays the result
📌 Simple Analogy

Think of a restaurant:

Model → Kitchen (prepares food/data)
View → Table (what the customer sees)
Controller → Waiter (takes orders, delivers food)
✅ Why MVC is Useful
Clear separation of concerns
Easier to maintain and scale
Code is more organized
Multiple developers can work independently

