Is there other common architectural pattern used in software development rather than MVC?
========================================================================================

Yes—MVC is just one of many architectural patterns. Different patterns are used depending on the problem, scale, and type of application. Here are some of the most common alternatives:

🔹 1. MVVM (Model–View–ViewModel)

Widely used in frontend frameworks.

Model → Data & logic
View → UI
ViewModel → Connects View and Model, handles UI logic

👉 Popular in frameworks like Angular and Vue.js.

Best for: Reactive UIs, two-way data binding.

🔹 2. MVP (Model–View–Presenter)

Similar to MVC but more structured.

Presenter replaces Controller
View is more passive
Presenter handles all logic and updates the View

Best for: Testable UI-heavy apps (common in older Android development).

🔹 3. Layered Architecture (N-Tier)

One of the most widely used in enterprise systems.

Presentation Layer (UI)
Business Logic Layer
Data Access Layer

Best for: Large business applications.

🔹 4. Microservices Architecture

Instead of one big app, you build many small services.

Each service handles one feature
Services communicate via APIs

👉 Used by companies like Netflix and Amazon.

Best for: Large-scale, distributed systems.

🔹 5. Monolithic Architecture

Everything is in a single codebase.

Simple to build and deploy
Harder to scale later

Best for: Small to medium projects or startups.

🔹 6. Event-Driven Architecture

Components communicate through events.

Producer emits events
Consumers react to them

Best for: Real-time systems (e.g., chat apps, notifications).

🔹 7. Clean Architecture (Uncle Bob)

Focuses on separation and independence.

Core logic is independent of frameworks
Organized in concentric layers

Best for: Long-term maintainability and testability.

🔹 8. Hexagonal Architecture (Ports & Adapters)

Also called “Ports and Adapters.”

Core logic in the center
External systems connect via adapters

Best for: Systems needing flexibility with databases, APIs, or UI changes.

🔹 9. Serverless Architecture

No need to manage servers.

Functions run on demand
Scales automatically

👉 Popular platforms include AWS Lambda.

Best for: Lightweight, scalable cloud apps.

🔹 Quick Comparison
Pattern	Best Use Case
MVC	Web apps
MVVM	Modern frontend apps
MVP	Testable UI apps
Layered	Enterprise systems
Microservices	Large scalable systems
Monolithic	Simple apps
Event-driven	Real-time systems
Clean/Hexagonal	Maintainable, flexible systems
Serverless	Cloud-native apps

